==English==
===Etymology===
The Greek prefix '''[[poly-]]''' + synthetic < Latin '''[[synthesis]]''' (collection, set, composition) < Greek '''[[σύνθεσις]]''' (composition) < '''[[συντίθημι]]''' (to put together, combine) < '''[[συν-]]''' (together) + '''[[τίθημι]]''' (to put, place) < Proto-Indo-European base '''[[*dhe-]]''' (to put, to do).

===Adjective===
#(''grammar:'') said of a language, characterized by a prevalence of relatively long words containing a large number of [[morpheme]]s. Typically, the morphemes are '''[[bound]]''' (i.e., they cannot stand alone as independent words). An example of a polysynthetic language is [[Ojibwe]], where:
:*baataanitaaanishinaabemong = "being able to speak Ojibwe."
:*ngiinitaaozhibii'amaadimin = "we used to write to each other."

